The [nuclear weapons of the United States](/Nuclear_weapons_of_the_United_States) represent the second-largest arsenal globally, a position it holds with a peculiar, grim distinction, trailing only behind [Russia](/Russia_and_weapons_of_mass_destruction). The [United States](/United_States) is the solitary nation to have unleashed [nuclear weapons in warfare](/Nuclear_warfare), an act that forever etched the [atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki](/Atomic_bombings_of_Hiroshima_and_Nagasaki) into the annals of [World War II](/World_War_II)'s brutal conclusion. The genesis of this formidable capability traces back to the clandestine [Manhattan Project](/Manhattan_Project), initiated in 1942, which propelled the US into the unenviable position of being the first [nuclear-armed country](/Nuclear-armed_country). Today, the US relies on a robust [nuclear triad](/Nuclear_triad) — a multi-faceted delivery system designed for both redundancy and overwhelming destructive potential. While its current focus remains on nuclear capabilities, the US has historically maintained extensive [chemical](/Chemical_weapons) and [biological weapons](/Biological_weapons) programs, which it has since renounced. The nation is a signatory and ratifier of key international accords aimed at curbing the spread and use of such armaments, including the [Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty](/Non-Proliferation_Treaty) (NPT), the [Biological Weapons Convention](/Biological_Weapons_Convention) (BWC), and the [Chemical Weapons Convention](/Chemical_Weapons_Convention) (CWC).

As of 2025 &#91;update&#93;, the [United States](/United_States) actively deploys a staggering approximate total of 1,770 warheads. These instruments of global consequence are primarily managed under the purview of [Strategic Command](/United_States_Strategic_Command) &#91;a&#93;, forming the backbone of its aforementioned [nuclear triad](/Nuclear_triad). A detailed breakdown reveals the chilling precision of this deployment: approximately 970 warheads are carried by [Trident II](/UGM-133_Trident_II) [submarine-launched ballistic missiles](/Submarine-launched_ballistic_missile), silently patrolling the depths aboard Ohio-class submarines. An additional 400 warheads are housed within silo-based [Minuteman III](/Minuteman_III) [intercontinental ballistic missiles](/Intercontinental_ballistic_missile), poised in the heartland. Rounding out the triad are 300 bombs and cruise missiles, designated for delivery by the stealthy [B-2 Spirit](/Northrop_B-2_Spirit) and the venerable [B-52 Stratofortress](/Boeing_B-52_Stratofortress) bombers. Beyond its own borders, the US also engages in [nuclear sharing](/Nuclear_sharing) arrangements, specifically [forward deploying nuclear weapons](/Nuclear_sharing) in the form of approximately 100 [B61 bombs](/B61_nuclear_bomb) across six European [NATO](/NATO) member states: [Belgium](/Belgium_and_weapons_of_mass_destruction), [Germany](/Germany_and_weapons_of_mass_destruction), [Italy](/Italy_and_weapons_of_mass_destruction), the [Netherlands](/Netherlands_and_weapons_of_mass_destruction), [Turkey](/Turkey_and_weapons_of_mass_destruction), and the [United Kingdom](/Nuclear_weapons_of_the_United_Kingdom). The full US warhead inventory, a number that fluctuates with the tides of geopolitics and dismantlement efforts, totals 5,177 warheads. Of these, 1,930 warheads are maintained for reserve use, while a further 1,477 are awaiting the slow, methodical process of dismantlement, a testament to the enduring cost of past decisions.

The [United States](/United_States) conducted its inaugural [nuclear test](/Nuclear_test), code-named [Trinity](/Trinity_(nuclear_test)), a mere three weeks before it unleashed the horrifying reality of atomic warfare on the cities of [Hiroshima and Nagasaki](/Atomic_bombings_of_Hiroshima_and_Nagasaki). This act of unprecedented destruction, while bringing an end to [World War II](/World_War_II), simultaneously ignited the embers of the [Cold War](/Cold_War)'s infamous [nuclear arms race](/Nuclear_arms_race). The perceived global balance of power was dramatically altered in 1949 when the [Soviet Union](/Soviet_Union) successfully executed [its first nuclear test](/RDS-1). This development spurred the US into an even more dangerous escalation, leading to the rapid development and testing of the world's first true [thermonuclear weapon](/Thermonuclear_weapons), the terrifying device dubbed [Ivy Mike](/Ivy_Mike), which detonated with unimaginable force on November 1, 1952. Throughout the 1950s, the US began to strategically [station nuclear weapons overseas](/Nuclear_sharing) in various locations across Europe and East Asia, a clear projection of power and a tangible commitment to its allies, albeit one that placed these regions squarely in the crosshairs. The global tensions surrounding these deployments reached a fever pitch in 1962 during the [Cuban Missile Crisis](/Cuban_Missile_Crisis), an event universally regarded as an agonizingly [close call](/Nuclear_close_calls) with the unthinkable prospect of [World War III](/World_War_III), a moment where humanity collectively held its breath and, by some cosmic fluke, managed to avert absolute catastrophe.

Between 1945 and 1992, the [United States](/United_States) embarked on an exhaustive series of [1,054 nuclear tests](/List_of_nuclear_weapons_tests_of_the_United_States). These detonations, each an act of controlled destruction on an epic scale, were primarily conducted at the [Nevada Test Site](/Nevada_Test_Site) and the desolate expanses of the [Pacific Proving Grounds](/Pacific_Proving_Grounds). In a belated, yet significant, gesture towards global stability, the US signed the [Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty](/Comprehensive_Nuclear-Test-Ban_Treaty) in 1996, indicating a formal cessation of such explosive demonstrations, even if the underlying capabilities remained.

The [US chemical weapons program](/United_States_chemical_weapons_program) first took root [during World War I](/Chemical_weapons_in_World_War_I), a conflict that tragically normalized the use of such insidious agents. Over the subsequent decades, particularly during the protracted [Cold War](/Cold_War), the US amassed a substantial arsenal of these weapons, primarily consisting of the deadly nerve agents [sarin](/Sarin) and [VX](/VX_(nerve_agent)), alongside the blistering agent [mustard gas](/Mustard_gas). These weapons were not merely stockpiled; they were strategically deployed abroad, notably in Okinawa and West Germany, only to be withdrawn in [1971](/Operation_Red_Hat) and [1990](/Operation_Steel_Box) respectively, a slow recognition of their inherent dangers. Disturbingly, the [Central Intelligence Agency](/Central_Intelligence_Agency)'s infamous [MKUltra](/MKUltra) program also delved into the shadowy realm of [psychochemical warfare](/Psychochemical_warfare), exploring the weaponization of compounds like the [BZ incapacitating agent](/3-Quinuclidinyl_benzilate) – a chilling testament to the lengths to which state agencies would go to control or incapacitate perceived adversaries, blurring ethical lines into an unrecognizable mess. In a significant policy shift, the US committed to the systematic destruction of its entire chemical weapons arsenal in 1991, a monumental task finally accomplished by 2023 at an astronomical total cost of US$40 billion – a fittingly high price for undoing decades of dangerous proliferation.

Concurrently, the [US biological weapons program](/United_States_biological_weapons_program) operated for a significant period, from 1943 until its formal renunciation in 1969. During this time, the program actively weaponized and stockpiled a terrifying array of [biological agents](/Biological_agent), including those responsible for [anthrax](/Anthrax), [botulism](/Botulism), [brucellosis](/Brucellosis), [Q-fever](/Q-fever), [toxic shock syndrome](/Toxic_shock_syndrome), and the [Venezuelan equine encephalitis virus](/Venezuelan_equine_encephalitis_virus). The official renouncement of this program in 1969 coincided with a similar commitment to forgo the first use of chemical weapons, marking a rare, albeit temporary, moment of restraint in the relentless pursuit of ever more destructive capabilities.

